OL,3,C'World's oldest calendar' found carved
OL,4,Conto ancient monument
OL,6,FThe world's oldest calendar, carved
OL,7,Fonto an ancient pillar around 12,000
OL,8,Fyears ago, has been discovered by UK
OL,9,Farchaeologists.
OL,11,FThe timekeeping system, unearthed at
OL,12,Fthe Gobekli Tepe site in Turkey,
OL,13,Fsuggests people were accurately
OL,14,Frecording dates 10,000 years before it
OL,15,Fwas documented in Greece in 150 BC.
OL,17,FAnalysing the markings, a team led by
OL,18,Fthe University of Edinburgh found 365
OL,19,F"V" symbols etched on one of the
OL,20,Fpillars at the site, each thought to
OL,21,Frepresent a single day.
